# Sound

- SB Pro, SB16 seem promising, however QEMU seems to have bugs / issues related to writing drivers in the past:
https://forum.osdev.org/viewtopic.php?t=39652

a quick glance at QEMU's bug trackers mentions some of these issues are still under works or 'not yet understood', and SB16 support isn't even maintained, so it's safer to assume it's been abandoned (ancient card)

- AC'97 is a bit more complicated but probably a good choice for now.
	- connected into PCI

Direct Memory Access (DMA):
A method for hardware to read/write system memory without involving the CPU for every transfer.

Buffer Descriptor List (BDL):
core DMA mechanism AC97 uses to transfer audio data between system memory and the codec.
set up buffers in memory with audio data ahead of time, and point the AC97 at it,
the DMA controller will consume them automatically while the CPU does other things.
the BDL is a ring buffer array of 32 entries, each entry being 8 bytes. this includes:
- physical address of the audio buffer
- number of samples in this buffer
- control bits (flags)

important flags include IOC (Interrupt On Completion) and BUP (Buffer Underrun Policy) - what to do if the controller runs out of buffers (output silence, stop, etc.). the other are reserved

basic flow (from https://wiki.osdev.org/AC97):
/* reset the controller */
- write the global reset bit to NAMBAR + 0x2C (global control register)
- wait for it to clear (poll until the bit reads back as 0)
- wait some amount for the codec to complete its cold reset

/* ready codec */
- poll until the codec ready bit in NAMBAR + 0x30 is set (global status register)

/* configure codec */
- set the volume of the desired output (Master Volume Register is NAM register 0x02, which is speakers)
- optionally, set the sample rate here (default is 48000Hz) via register 0x2C
- write PCM out volume to codec register 0x18


/* BDL setup */
- allocate a ring buffer of 32 audio buffer entries, fill them with audio data
- addon: write the *physical* address and sample count for each entry, and set IOC flag on entries from which you want interrupts from

/* start playback */
- write an initial LVI to NAMBAR + 0x15 (PCM out last valid index)
- write the run/pause bit (0x1) to NAMBAR + 0x1B (PCM out transfer control)

/* runtime loop */
- poll or handle interrupts from NAMBAR + 0x16 (PCM out status register) for buffer completion
- refill the consumed buffer with new audio data
- advance LVI by 1 modulo 32 and write it to NAMBAR + 0x15
loop


References:
https://web.archive.org/web/20210422185924/https://www.intel.com/assets/pdf/manual/252751.pdf
https://web.archive.org/web/20180508155315id_/http://www-inst.eecs.berkeley.edu/~cs150/Documents/ac97_r23.pdf
https://web.archive.org/web/20170226174953im_/http://www.intel.com/content/dam/doc/manual/io-controller-hub-7-hd-audio-ac97-manual.pdf


# PCI - Peripheral Component Interconnect

See:
https://wiki.osdev.org/PCI
https://wiki.osdev.org/PCI_Express


>The PCI bus was defined to establish a high performance, low cost local bus.
- non-extended verison has an upper limit of some amount, due to [physics shenanigans from devices affecting capacitance on the bus](https://electronics.stackexchange.com/questions/470771/what-is-the-maximum-number-of-devices-a-single-pci-bus-can-handle) I suspect this isn't present in code, but was a part of the reason for the shift to PCIe (extended), so likely best to not use legacy hardware in unintended ways, even if the emulation might support it (TODO verify)
several sites report conflicting number of devices, would require manually checking but that's outside the scope of this project for now - we only wish to read AC97. even setting up PCI device enumeration through the bus is overkill :^)

- PCI devices are accessible through a load/store mechanism:
	- memory address (MMIO) space
	- I/O address spaces
	- *Configuration* space

The *Host Bus* connects the CPU and memory subsystem to the PCI bus

Each device is addressed through a three tuple: `Bus:Device:Function` (BDF). Bus is 8 bits, device is 5 bits, function
is 3 bits.
Note that this means that there can be _multiple_ PCI buses.

Every PCI function exposes 256 bytes of configuration space, standardized register layout to identify and configure the device without device-specific knowledge.

QEMU PCI notes:
- reports max of 32 multi-function devices per bus
- bridges have two PCI interface - primary, secondary
gotchas:
- highly parallel shared-bus architecture holds it back by limiting bus speed and scalability
- simple load/store, flat-memory model less robust than routed packet-based model

PCIe improvements:
- point to point bus topology
- each device sits on its own dedicated bus, which is called a *link*
*continued in QEMU pci presentation*

PCI Configuration
- I/O mapped
- addresses identical across machines
- only supports 256 bytes/device
- only supports 256 buses

PCI IO Space -> PCI Configuration Space (header + device specific configuration space)

Comand Register:
- provides ability for a device to respond to and generate PCI cycles
- 0 => device is *logically* disconnected from the PCI bus

Status Register:
- used to record status information for PCI bus related events
* device may not need to implement all bits, depending on device functionality:
	- interrupt status (3)
	- capabilities list (4)
	- 66 Mhz compatible (5) [assumed 33Mhz otherwise]
	- Reserved (bit 6)
	- Fast back-to-back capable (7)
	- Master data parity error (8)
	- DEVSEL timing (9)
	- (10) [00 - fast; 01 - medium; 10 - slow]
	- signaled target abort
	- received target abort
	- received master abort
	- signaled system error
	- detected parity error

Configuration Space
256 bytes are required per device specifically for configuration registers. These provide software-driven initialization
and configuration for each device or target on the PCI bus via the Configuration Space Address. Read/Write cycles are
used to access the configuration space for each target device. the IDSEL signal acts as the "chip select" signal.

Once an address is written to 0xCF8, a read or write to 0xCFC causes the host bridge to initiate a PCI configuration
transaction on the bus

Configuration - Capabilities
- set of registers added to a linked list
- enabled if "capabilites" is set ON in status register
capabilities examples:
	- MSI / MSI X
	- PCI-X
	- PCIe

Configuration - Base Address Registers (BARs) // lol
- BAR dual usage:
	- Used to determine how much memory space or I/O space the device requires
	- stores the base address of the memory region which is used to access the device registers

Configuration space triggering - PCIe (ECAM)
- Memory mapped
- Supports 4k bytes/devices
	- Each device has its own 4k memory page
- Requires up to 28 bits of memory
	- 256MB
- Supports 256 buses per base address

Configuration PCIe Configuration - PCIe Extended Capabilities
- It is not the PCI Express "capability"
- begins at offset 100h
- Resembles PCI Capability structure

Configuration - Multiple host bridges / Root complexes
- NUMA-how servers scales up
- A PCI host bridge can be connected to a single NUMA node
- device assignment for a VM with multiple NUMA nodes

PCI Hot Plug
- concept of removing or inserting a standard PCI adapter card from a system without interrupting normal system operation or powering down the system as a whole
ACPI hot plug, as part of ACPI spec

Interrupts handling
Legacy interrupts
- Legacy interrupts are dedicated side-band signals
- Multiple interrupt signals may share a single physical line
MSI
- In-band messages are implemented as memory writes to an address with a data value, as specified by software
	- Required for PCI express devices, optional for PCI drives
	- Maximum of 32 MSIs per function

- MSI has a number of distinct advantages over INTx
	- Sharing of interrupt vectors is eliminated
	- Devices may have multiple interrupts per function

